{
  "original_content": "# Induction of Supervisors: Key Legislation\n\nThis document compiles the critical labor legislation for supervisor work, employer obligations, and principles of managing workplace well-being.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Comprehensive Supervisor Skills\n\nThe supervisor's main task is to implement the company's strategy by guiding their subordinates. Skills consist of three areas:\n- **Will:** Desire to act as a supervisor, self-awareness, and desire to develop.\n- **Skill:** Communication and interaction skills, emotional intelligence, and use of management tools.\n- **Knowledge:** Strategic goals, understanding of role and responsibilities, and legal matters.\n\nThe supervisor acts as the employer's representative and is responsible for the unit's operations, finances, and supporting employees' professional development.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Managing Workplace Well-being\n\nWorkplace well-being is safe, healthy, and productive work in a well-managed organization.\n- **Development targets:** Individual health, functionality of the work community, work environment, and professional skills.\n- **Ethical management:** Value-based operation that commits to improving productivity and well-being simultaneously.\n- **Metrics:** Sick absences, accident frequency, staff turnover, quality of development conversations, and workplace atmosphere surveys.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Induction and Work Guidance\n\nInduction is the employer's responsibility. Its objective is to create a positive attitude, promote independence, and ensure occupational health and safety.\n- **Content:** Organization's practices, employment contract terms, working hours, salary matters, occupational health care, safety issues, and personal responsibility areas.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Key Labor Legislation\n\n### Employment Contract Act (55/2001)\nEstablishes the foundation for employment relationship matters.\n- **Employer obligations:** Equal treatment, anti-discrimination, ensuring occupational safety, and written explanation of work conditions.\n- **Probationary period:** Maximum 6 months.\n\n### Occupational Safety and Health Act (738/2002)\nBasic law of occupational safety.\n- **Employer obligation:** Ensure employees' safety and health, identify hazards, and assess risks.\n- **Employee obligation:** Follow instructions, use protective equipment, and report deficiencies.\n\n### Working Hours Act (872/2019)\n- **Regular working hours:** 8 h/day and 40 h/week. Possibility for flexible working hours and working time bank.\n- **Rest periods:** Generally at least 11 h daily rest and 35 h weekly rest.\n\n### Other key laws:\n- **Non-Discrimination Act:** Promotes equality between women and men (equality plan mandatory if at least 30 employees).\n- **Non-Discrimination Act:** Prevents discrimination (age, origin, religion, etc.).\n- **Act on the Protection of Privacy in Working Life:** Processing of personal data and camera surveillance.\n- **Occupational Health Care Act:** Obliges arranging services to prevent illness.\n- **Annual Holidays Act:** Defines holiday length, pay, and timing.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Collective Agreements (TES/VES)\n\n- **General applicability:** TES applies to unorganized employers throughout the industry as well.\n- **Minimum requirements:** TES defines minimum wages and other conditions that must not be exceeded. Locally, better conditions can be agreed upon.",
